<font color="#FF0000">REGRETS PART II</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jan 18 10:23:12 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
Ed <br>
You and I, all of us didn't go to Vietnam, to kill women, children or innocent civilians.<br><br>
Communist aggression brought us to South East Asia, and while the enemy purposely killed, women and children and often made them run with them, or hid behind them as they shot at us, we did do that. <br><br>
We value life too much, regretted it when innocent children were killed, but we didn’t place them in harm’s way, the enemy did this.<br><br>
I don't know if I killed women or children I do know I shot some of them, but it was not me that placed them in harm's way. It was communism, their disregard for life, dictated they were expendable for the goal they wanted to obtain. While I regret having shot and possibly having killed women and children, I do not regret having served there. <br><br>
 If I hadn’t gone, if you hadn’t been there others would not have lived (US Military personnel as well as Vietnamese civilians), and because you shot at the enemy and I shot at the enemy who used these tactics in war, the enemy soon learned that it would not prevent us from killing them. Civilian learned this as well, of the Vietnamese I have talked to regarding those type of causalities, I have not found one, that blames us for the lost of those lives under those circumstances, in fact they condemned and still blame the enemy, the NVA communist soldier for the lost of those lives.<br><br>
None the less, we regret it, but the evil heart of communism soldier does not, I don’t know who said this but it has value.<br><br>
“For those who fought for it, life has a flavor the protected will never know.”<br><br>
Bro, thanks for being there, for being here, thanks for doing your duty and for having a heart.<br><br>
Cook Barela<br>

